commentBody:
@Ann 
CHEEZ-IT came to mind pretty quickly, because I had just seen a commercial for a CHEEZ-IT spin-off product called Snap'd while watching the Olympics and I'd wondered if I would ever see that as crossword fill.  (Worlds  collide.)

TWANG seemed slightly off for the clue, but as you note,Drawl was wrong today.

@Jeremy 

I don’t get how this has already gotten so many recs. Shah, Sahl, Mao, EAP, erg are all pretty standard Xword fill. (Geez, erg is making a run at emu triteness, almost half an oboe.) Aro has also made a comeback, albeit with a more contemporary definition.  As BA notes elsewhere, we’ve seen arepa and arepas recently, a number of times.  Sensate shows up every now and then. All pre-Fagliano as editor.

Nyuorican was fresh, and discoverable from the crosses.  That’s a good thing.

@Jeremy 

Too bad Daniel didn't include "AS CROSS AS TWO STICKS" in the puzzle.... 



EMUs cowering in the corners for fear of tongue-lashing....

@Jeb Jones 

I find looking for mistakes the most burdensome thing about doing crosswords.  My heart sinks whenever I finish and don't get Mr. Happy Piano.

Especially hard, when I'm grinding over where *I think* the mistake is, and not even looking at where the mistake *actually* is.

@Barry Ancona 

And also, they live in areas where the available array of prepared ethnic foods is limited to the Trinity of Italian, Chinese and Mexican...




(They sell AREPAS in the refrigerated aisle at Costco, folks.)

@jb 

With that combination of useful letters, it's not surprising that Mr. SAHL continues to be found frequently in crosswords.  But it's not like he was a nobody; he definitely was a pioneer of modern comedy.

What surprises me is that as a native of Montreal, as some of the clues listed at xwordinfo.com indicate, he shortened his given name Morton to Mort...given what it means in French.

@Michael S 

POE gets a lot of space in X-World.  Hardly new.

And I plan to say "DASH IT!" quite often now (as necessary, as when the ice cubes miss my glass as they shoot out of the dispenser on the fridge.)  Join me!

@Esmerelda 

Good luck with your construction efforts! I don’t know if having a puzzle published is a goal, but if so, I hope that works out. 

Learning how to construct a puzzle makes one appreciate how difficult it is to construct a good puzzle.

@Bill 

That was even MORE elegant and fun when worked upward/backward from bottom to top!

Sorry about your headache!  Suggest a strong massage of the spaces between pinkies and ring fingers and webbing between thumb and index fingers.  Attention to toes similarly can help.  (Not making this up.)

@dk 

No rebus! Waaaaah!



EMUs cheated me

@Tom 
@Brendan

Yeah, I'm curious, too.  Because if it's NUYORICAN, I promise you it's just as exotic to a midwesterner (mostly)  like me as it is to Brits.

@Amy 

Milk crates, the real ones that carried actual milk, were a huge staple in my dorm and working at a camp.

Honestly, nothing has ever been found to be better. I wish it was still socially acceptable to adorn one's home with bright orange milk crates full of important things! 😉

@Hooper 

So is this a Monday puzzle or a Wednesday puzzle? 

I beat my Monday average by a few seconds, but according to xwstats.com, most solvers found it harder than the typical Tuesday.

@R.J. Smith
We each know different stuff.  I sailed thru this in about 2/3 my average Tues time.

SHAH was easy for me.  My Sister lived in Iran for 2 years just before the SHAH fell.

@sotto voce 

Well, dang, you triggered another.  Actually, what’s bigger than an earworm? An ear serpent?  The old Civil Wars covering MJ:

<a href="https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=441mR2zsQbg" target="_blank">https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=441mR2zsQbg</a>

@Bill 

....or how funny they may look on clothing:

<a href="https://www.gocomics.com/speedbump/2024/08/03" target="_blank">https://www.gocomics.com/speedbump/2024/08/03</a>

@Mick 

I knew the word, but don’t know much about NUYORICAN culture other than what I have seen in movies and TV. 

It’s been depressing to read some of today’s comments that are so dismissive of NUYORICAN as a puzzle entry.

@Steph 
That's why I had "ace" in first, changed it with the crosses. 

I don't know enough about the subject to argue with it, so I just accepted the answer.

@KandB I did have to Google for the proper definition to be true since language is tricky.

The primary sources I found via Google specifically mention sexual feelings, with the default from Google/Oxford Languages offered: showing, feeling, or relating to sexual desire.

What can ya do? :shrug:

@Esmerelda 

My first few attempts weren’t punishable, either. It’s tempting to add a few black squares when you have an unfillable grid, and before you know it, you have too many black squares, too many three-letter words, or both. 

I haven’t had a decent theme idea in months and consequently haven’t constructed any grids in a while. But I do enjoy doing it when it goes well.

@Tessa 

There was a time when a certain state was or had The Biggest of Everything, and some folks there called themselves TEXICANS.  

I had to work a bit to parse that, but Oh, Okay.

@Barry Ancona -- It's REALLY bad.  Not just NUYORICAN, but I also had to look up Loisada!

But then they say that NYC is a city of neighborhoods.  So that if you've always lived downtown and I've always lived uptown in the Carnegie Hill neighborhood, I guess it sort of proves the point.

You should also know that poetry pretty much ended for me when they took away the rhyme -- I'm with Frost who said that writing poetry that doesn't rhyme is like playing tennis with the net down -- so that the NUYORICANS are far from the only contemporary poets I'm unfamiliar with.  Don't, for example, get me started on Sylvia Plath -- and she's not even all that contemporary. :)

@Bob T. 

Thank you! That makes sense.

All my loyalty cards are virtual these days and I don't recall any loyalty cards that were fewer than 10 punches.

